Certainly! Here's a simple C# program that generates a playful riddle about a perky pup named "Peppy" who enjoys prancing in the park. The program includes alliteration for a whimsical touch.

```csharp
using System;

class RiddleGenerator
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Generate the riddle
        string riddle = GenerateRiddle("Peppy");

        // Display the riddle
        Console.WriteLine(riddle);
    }

    static string GenerateRiddle(string pupName)
    {
        // Construct the riddle with alliteration
        return $"In the park, a perky pup prances, " +
               $"playfully pouncing with pure passion. " +
               $"Who is this charming canine, " +
               $"proudly parading with poise? " +
               $"It's none other than {pupName}!";
    }
}
```

This program defines a `GenerateRiddle` method that creates a playful riddle using alliteration. The riddle is then printed to the console. You can run this C# program to see the riddle output, which includes several examples of alliteration for a whimsical effect.
